quote:Originally posted by ronelson:His point still stands. My $10 cheapo mouse dates back to whenever optical mice became cool again and it still works. Sounds like quality to me, but without the $150 pricetag. You're confusing high quality production with high quality design; they aren't the same thing.I've got a great Intellimouse that will last me for years, but there are some design decisions that were made that aren't as comfortable for me as they could be. If I cared enough (or had a need, such as photo editing, for example), I'd look into getting a mouse that was more suited to the way I grip and click. As it stands now, I'll settle for what I have since I'm lazy and don't use my mouse in a way that would justify a pricetag over, say, $25.The mouse I use for my job is even lower design-quality than at home, but because of what my job entails, I don't miss any of the features it doesn't have. Well, I sometimes miss being able to hit "back" on webpages without clicking a link on the browser, but not as much as I would if my home mouse didn't have the feature.And I couldn't survive having a mouse without a scroll wheel at home or work. One of the other desks has a mouse like that, and it's like I've suddenly lost a finger, or something.For me, a high-priced, advanced design mouse wouldn't be worth the upgrade, but for many other people, it's worth every penny.^-.-^
